                  <handDesc>
                     
                     <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                        <seg type="script">Fine, regular.</seg>
                        <seg type="ink">Black; red.</seg>
                        <date notBefore="1250" notAfter="1350">Mid-13th – mid-14th century
                           (?)</date>
                        <seg type="rubrication">Several groups of lines on the incipit page of Texts
                           II and III, alternating with black lines; concluding formula of Texts I
                           and II; chapter titles; elements of the punctuation signs and of the text
                           dividers, crux ansata, coronis, qom-sign, zǝya-sign.</seg>
                        <note>The Ms. is written in the same ancient hand j as the text on <locus target="#153rv">153rv</locus> in<ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/ESum050">UM-050</ref>(Kings 2 18:32-19:15). The leaf should be placed before
                              <locus target="#66">66</locus>.</note>
                        <note> Some ancient/distinctive features: <list>
                              <item> - መ has the loops not completely separated, of triangular shape
                                 (e.g., <locus target="#44vb">44vb</locus> ls. 3 and 13). </item>
                              <item> - the 6th order marker of ው is attached to the upper horizontal
                                 stroke of the letter (e.g., <locus target="#49ra">49ra</locus> ls.
                                 1 and 18, 74vb l. 7). </item>
                              <item> - the 6th order marker of ሕ, ቅ and ት is curved at the top of
                                 the letter and cannot be easily distinguished from the 1st order of
                                 the same letters (e.g., <locus target="#31va">31va</locus>
                                 <locus target="#20">20</locus>, 32rb <locus target="#17">17</locus>, 34vb <locus target="#18">18</locus>, 44va <locus target="#13">13</locus>). </item>
                              <item> - the 6th order marker of እ has a long horizontal stroke toward
                                 the left (e.g. <locus target="#31vb">31vb</locus>
                                 <locus target="#10">10</locus>, 68ra <locus target="#14">14</locus>). </item>
                              <item> - ዓ has the 5th order marker attached to the centre of the body
                                 (e.g. <locus target="#49vr">49vr</locus>b <locus target="#25">25</locus>, 68rb <locus target="#18">18</locus>). </item>
                              <item> - ዱ has two horizontal strokes on the right side (e.g., <locus target="#44va">44va</locus> l. 6). </item>
                              <item> - the 7th order marker of ሮ and ኖ is attached directly to the
                                 downstroke (e.g., <locus target="#30vb">30vb</locus>
                                 <locus target="#13">13</locus> and 14, 31ra <locus target="#25">25</locus>, 34vb l. 2). </item>
                              <item> - numerals are written without dashes (e.g., <locus target="#10vb">10vb</locus>, 51rb, 51v). </item>
                              <item> - the qom-sign is inserted in the left margin of the column
                                 (e.g., <locus target="#26va">26va</locus>, 48va) or embedded within
                                 the text (e.g., <locus target="#44vb">44vb</locus>, 47rb, 64vb) </item>
                              <item> - the zǝyä-sign is inserted in the left margin of the column
                                    (<locus target="#54rb">54rb</locus>) or embedded within the text
                                 (e.g., <locus target="#44vb">44vb</locus>,
                                 64vb)
                              </item>
                              <item> - sentence dividers are accompanied by paragraphs signs.</item>
                           </list>
                        </note>
                     </handNote>
